ld both constrains social representation and informs its content. Most importantly, Sorrell shows how members of a given community not only represent but transform a shared world—and how those practices of representation may, and should, be improved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329650740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823296507423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823296507/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK